# Force LF for files that EXECUTE on Linux (the EC2 box). The dev machine is Windows
# with core.autocrlf=true, which makes `git archive` inject CRLF into shell scripts and
# systemd units → `$'\r': command not found` / `set: pipefail<CR>: invalid option` at
# runtime on the box. eol=lf pins LF in the working tree AND in `git archive` output,
# independent of the local autocrlf setting. (Found 2026-06-30 during the CloudWatch
# publisher deploy; protects the ADR-0032 cutover scripts too.)
*.sh      text eol=lf
*.service text eol=lf
*.timer   text eol=lf

# COUNTERSIGNED RESEARCH ARTIFACTS — the owner's countersign binds an exact SHA-256 of
# the file BYTES. With core.autocrlf=true a fresh clone would materialize these as CRLF
# (e.g. MR-002 v1.1 rev 3: 35,053 B LF -> 35,688 B CRLF), producing a different hash and
# silently voiding the binding. eol=lf pins LF in the working tree and in `git archive`.
docs/implementation/TradingWorkbench_MR002_PreRegistration_*.md text eol=lf
docs/implementation/evidence/mr_002/**                          text eol=lf

# ⚠ BINARY ARTIFACTS MUST NEVER BE EOL-CONVERTED.
#
# The `evidence/mr_002/**` rule above matches EVERYTHING in that tree — including the gzipped
# data archives. Git then treats them as text, and its clean filter STRIPS the CR from any CRLF
# byte pair that happens to occur inside the compressed stream. `anchors.csv.gz` contains 8 such
# pairs; a single `git add` would delete those bytes and destroy the archive. They have shown as
# permanently "modified" while being byte-identical to HEAD, which is the symptom of exactly this.
#
# Listed after the rules above so these win.
*.gz      binary
*.parquet binary
*.duckdb  binary
*.sqlite  binary
*.xlsx    binary
*.docx    binary
*.pptx    binary
*.pdf     binary
*.png     binary
*.jpg     binary
